tionary England -- t13 An Irish Protestation? Oaths and the Confederation of Kilkenny -- t14 ‘Whereat his wife tooke great greef & died’: dying of sorrow and killing in anger in seventeenth-century Ireland -- tBibliography for John Walter -- tIndex -- tTabula Gratulatoria0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn outstanding collection, bringing together some of the leading historians of this period with some of the field's rising stars, which examines key issues in popular politics, the negotiation of power, strategies of legitimation,and the languages of politics.One of the most notable currents in social, cultural and political historiography is the interrogation of the categories of 'elite' and 'popular' politics and their relationship to each other, as well as the exploration of why andhow different sorts of people engaged with politics and behaved politically. While such issues are timeless, they hold a special importance for a society experiencing rapid political and social change, like early modern England.No one has done more to define these agendas for early modern historians than John Walter. His work has been hugely influential, and at its heart has been the analysis of the political agency of ordinary people. The essays in thisvolume engage with the central issues of Walter's work, ranging across the politics of poverty, dearth and household, popular political consciousness and practice more broadly, and religion and politics during the English revolution. This outstanding collection, bringing together some of the leading historians of this period with some of the field's rising stars, will appeal to anyone interested in the social, cultural and political history of early modern England or issues of popular political consciousness and behaviour more generally. MICHAEL J. BRADDICK is professor of history at the University of Sheffield. PHIL WITHINGTON is professor of history at the Universityof Sheffield. CONTRIBUTORS: Michael J. Braddick, J. C. Davis, Amanda Flather, Steve Hindle, Mark Knights, John Morrill, Alexandra Shepard, Paul Slack, Richard M. Smith, Clodagh Tait, Keith Thomas, Phil Withington, Andy Wood, Keith Wrightson.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEarly Modern History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBritish Politics.  aBritish history.  aEarly Modern England.  aElite politics.  aEnglish Revolution.  aEnglish Society.  aHistorian.  aHistoriography.  aJohn Walter.  aPolitical Consciousness.  aPolitical Language.  aPopular politics.  aSocial Change.  aSocial history.1 aBraddick, Michael J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraddick, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraddick, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavis, J. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, J.C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlather, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHindle, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnights, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorrill, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShepard, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlack, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Richard M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTait, Clodagh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThoma